segments.text: Professor Katz, tell us about how the entry of women affected Texas A&M women's students.
Well, I think that had considerable, that happened, that came about much more smoothly than the matter of dropping the core as a requirement.
When the girls first came in, why they came in is they had to be the wife of a GI,
or the wife of any student, of course, or they'd be in the family of some professor or employee of the state.
And then it got to where they...
I think they actually had a lawsuit that never came to trial, but if it was good for...

If it was good for this young lady because of her circumstance of being born in the right family or married to the right fellow, why, here's another one over here equally deserving, they think, and why couldn't she go?
Why should she have to travel over to Sam Houston or some other place?
So they put the heat on and brought the wide-open...
admission of coeds.
Did you have many female students in your engineering classes?
A few, yes.
How did their performance measure against their male counterparts?
By and large, they were above average.
Like spatial abilities supposedly attributed to females didn't enter in?
In my opinion, the bulk of them wouldn't undertake engineering unless they had excelled in their high school work.
They were above average students or they would not have tackled engineering.
And they were still above average students.
I had a few.
What do you think was the reason for such small numbers of black students enrolled in engineering?
Well, it's preparation.
Preparation.
One, they would get in and a lot more started than stayed.
By and large, they would avoid engineering because the propaganda was that this is a real difficult course.
You've got to have mathematics, you've got to do this, you've got to do that.
You've got to speak thermodynamics in order to succeed in engineering.
And they would take the path of least resistance, either go to prayer with you or go to work.
And a little later on, they'd get in the Army.
You mentioned that while you were at A&M from 58 to 76, most of your time was put into heavy teaching loads rather than the research.
Do you think that the trend has changed too much as for professors to spend more time on research than they do on teaching?
Yes.
Do you think that can be detrimental to a university?
That's a moot question.
Research works.
if associated with teaching, can very much improve teaching.
For instance, my teaching down at Kelly Air Force Base, I was teaching...
I was teaching metallurgy here, and I was teaching metallurgy down there.
Well, the people I was teaching down there were the people that were actually doing the metallurgical work, working in the metallurgical laboratory
And when they had failures on aircraft, they would bring the parts in there to be examined.
Why did this fail?
And then I was giving them a general background so that they would know not only how something failed, but why.
Why the material was treated as it was and how it might have been otherwise.
heat-treated or alloyed or whatnot.
And the association I had there very much enriched the classes that I taught here, because I had examples.
I would bring pieces and parts up there and show them, and you get the attention when you do that.
It's not just something out of the book.
What about, can some research though be detrimental as far as teaching goes?

If a fellow gets himself in a bind in research, most all of that has got to, they have to make proposals, and they have deadlines on getting those proposals in, and they have to work, work, work day and night to make the goals on getting the proposals in.
And when they're working 15 hours a day on that, they're not going to work too much on their teaching.
They're going to get by as best they can.

And the same thing's true when they start making their reports and getting... Or when the research work gets into a critical phase where they're getting such good results or bad results, as the case may be, because...
Some research says they yield bad results.
If it's going to be bad, well, you want to find out.
But there are critical phases in that that make for neglect of the teaching work.
Another thing is that they put a fellow in and say he's half-time teaching and he's half-time research.
And it turns out both of them are about a three-quarter time job.
Because as a half-time researcher, he's got the same kind of reports that a full-time researcher has.
He's got the same kind of proposals to write up.
As a teacher, he's got the students coming in for contact, for help.
He's got the same extracurricular things to look out for that a full-time teacher has.
And it turns out that a half and half deal is about a three-quarter and three-quarter, and that turns out to be about a job and a half.
And I stand to be corrected on that.
I've done some research for it, by the way.
As you end your teaching career at A&M, how do changes occur as far as job opportunities for graduates over the years?
Oh, there's an ebb and flow.
you spoke of that you graduated in 1970, there was a low in employment opportunities along about then.
Well, by the time I retired, there was, all they had to do was have your name on a diploma, and it was a choice of jobs.
And it's still that way, although I understand.
A good engineering student has a typical four, five, or six, or as many offers as he's able to interview and solicit.
It is cyclical, and sometimes the need for more engineers
and less engineers.
Right now, the economic situation is such that these companies, they're still hiring, but they're cutting back on the numbers that they hire right now.
And that may serve to throttle a number of people who take engineering.
And eventually, when the economic situation comes into full bloom again,
Then, there may not be as many engineers as there is opportunities to go to work.
It cycles that way.
I don't know what we can do about it.
Russia hadn't figured out a good thing except to have too many engineers.
Oh, Russia has too many?
Oh, they have an enormous number of engineers.
Japan, as little as it is, graduates more engineers, I think, than the United States does.
And the bulk of these foreign students that come in here take engineering.
Aren't they mainly subsidized by their governments, the ones that come in?
Well, too many of them are subsidized by our government.
How's that?
Oh, one...
one deal or another.
See, after all, I worked on this Foreign Service thing for four years, and I was personally instrumental in sending a number of people over here for higher education, they called it.
And the ones I sent over were under a contract they had to go back.
But their way was paid over here by the American government under our foreign aid program.
And a lot of those countries, although they pay the students way over here, they're getting foreign aid from the United States in a treasury to treasury situation.
And part of the thing is that they send that people over here for education.
What was your experience as an engineering faculty member regarding international students?
Were they any different than regular American students?
Well, of course, various ones of them have various language problems.
And according to where they came from, they had
The reality of engineering facts or equipment or machinery and all, they had not been exposed to it.
It had been something that was academic.
Getting them to put their hands on the stuff and really get with it was a little more difficult, but by and large, most of them who come are superior students.
They've got a good mind.
You get them to get their hands dirty or something else.
Not really.
Not really.
I've had some of them try.
And some of them may have gotten away with it more than I think they got away with.
Do you ever see any of your farmers used to say, do you go somewhere, go to Houston or Dallas, do you ever run into them constantly?
Some of them come here sometimes.
I see my old students all the time.
When I go to meetings like the American Society of Engineering Education or the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, meetings like that, I always run into my old students.
While you were at university, were you ever under any pressure to work on a doctorate?
Yeah, well, yes.
The reason I had to make a choice between accepting an associate professor promotion, which was timely and I thought deserved and they thought deserved and so forth, if I had accepted that,
Then I would bar myself from getting a PhD at A&M.
That restriction.
Now, on that, I had some 24 hours to order a PhD or beyond a master's at that particular time.
Also, that opportunity to go overseas occurred about that same time.
And either I accepted those two things and got on with what I was doing, or I chucked the whole works there and refused the promotion and refused the overseas assignment and concentrated on the PhD.
While you were there, was there a lot of pressure for faculty members to publish their findings?
Oh, yes.
But I got around that by actually doing it.
You remember the book by Virgil Boring-Ferris called Thermodynamics?
Or the one called FAIRES?
Or the one in machine design?
textbook by Ferris.
He also wrote a book on mechanics.
He was a very prolific writer and a prolific researcher at the library level and he
I helped him revise a mechanics book, and I revised about 1,600 problems in that book.
I added new ones and so forth.
So, the publication business I got around there.
At least when I retired, when I got Professor Emeritus.
When did A&M become a publisher-parish institution as it is today?
Oh, I would say back through the 50s, 50s and 60s, the 60s more particularly.
And you remember when you said you got out in 1970?
And along then, why, there was a lull in opportunities to go into engineering or hiring
The numbers being hired was much less and the salaries offered was much less.
Along about that time, the academic institutions, A&M being one of them in particular here, they were able to go in and force their faculty to do writing
do research and whatnot, because they had such a high and privileged job.
And to hold that, they must excel.
And that of excelling was they must get the name before the public and research and write.
And the pressure came.
The pressure on that came right along with it.
Now, if you'll check up right now, there's been a lessening of that pressure because right now there's a scarcity of people in the engineering teaching profession.
Scarcity in engineering, not in other fields.
No.
And with that scarcity, you won't hear the wheels squeak on that publish or perish
There's some other area, Professor Katz, that you could elaborate on that might be of interest to this interview or this interview.
Oh, I think that some of the young faculty we have now come to us with their PhDs, their expertise, their know-how in the use of certain experimental equipment.
They come to us and one of the first things they must do is to carry on their research work and to carry on their research work
they must have some of that particular experimental equipment.
Most of it's expensive.
Whereas, the equipment that's already on hand might be able to do the same job, but these young experts don't know how to use this other equipment.
But they want something on which they are the expert.
And that is an expensive proposition from the standpoint of money, the standpoint of building use, the standpoint of utilization of equipment that's already on hand.
And those same people tend to have an inferiority that they hide.
don't want to get into an area in which they are not expert.
After all, they have a PhD.
And they hate to admit they don't know something.
So they go around trying to confine themselves to teaching a very few courses and using a relatively limited variety of equipment and doing a limited variety of research work.
And they're unfairly limiting themselves because they're afraid somebody will say he doesn't know everything.
An old-timer like me that taught 28 different courses in my time, when they needed a course taught, if I knew something at all about the field, I got with it and dug it out.
I've taught some courses I never had.
That's correct.
That's correct.
Has this made cost of engineering research much higher than it could be otherwise?
And with the scarcity of faculty applications,
why these applicants come in and they demand that they be permitted to do research in this particular field.
They teach these particular courses.
They must teach graduate courses.
And most of them, a lot of those that are teaching a graduate course would fall on their face trying to teach the undergraduate course that backs up that graduate course.
What do you mean by that?
Well, the most difficult courses in engineering are not the graduate courses.
They're the undergraduate courses that are the foundation, the fundamentals for those graduate courses.
You mean it's possible to teach some of the more advanced courses without really knowing those fundamentals?
Have them really taught those fundamentals.
And when you have not taught a course,
old father time comes in and takes away your expertise if you ever had any yeah i found that when you teach something you have to learn it

What I had asked earlier regarding this type of attitude toward my faculty members, does this increase the cost of engineering research and what it would be otherwise, the requirement for special equipment and so forth?
It increases the cost of teaching.
It increases the cost of some of those faculty members, the younger faculty members are promoted.
on the basis of their, well, on the basis of need, really.

You need somebody, and you've got to have, you've got so many applicants, and they won't come unless he gets an associate or an assistant professorship, or some of them demand that if they've got a little experience, they may only come in as a full professor.
And the only way you can get them is to do that.
And those
Those things are not in an orderly step-by-step process.
Of course, on the other hand, you can go for years and years, and a fellow stay in grade and use him up.
I probably had a life full of experience in that line.
I taught courses that full professors taught, and I was an associate professor for a long time there until, of course, I retired as a professor emeritus.
But the salary was kind of low in that job.
All honors.

well with all these changes then what you're implying or at least what i'm inferring is that the quality of the teaching has not changed in the last 30 years only the research may have souped up the progress but this really hasn't been that much change in the quality of teaching is that true and you find another thing they when there's been so much stuff added in the last
You're given any number of years you please to call out.
Five years, 10 years, or 50 years.
We're doing things now.
We have levels of technology, expertise in mathematics and computer work and so forth now that didn't exist then.
Now, if they're going to teach about those things,
What are they going to leave out?
It accumulates like history.
Something has to be left out.
When I was a student, 1928 to 1932, we didn't have any jet engines.
We didn't have any rocket engines.
Only rockets and fireworks.
We didn't have any radar.
We didn't have any antibiotics.
We didn't have any...
When I get my mind to it, I can name about 10 different major fields.
There was no digital computer.
The digital computer had just not been conceived at that time.
And the slide rule didn't go out of style until a year, 10 years, 10, 15 years ago, about 10 years ago.
And when you bring in the teaching of all of these new things, somehow you must.
And now they're telling us they must get into the field of robots.
And if you're going to teach all about robots, why, that's something extra.
What are you going to leave out?
A four-year college course is still a four-year college course.
And I'll cite one more thing.
When I was a student, we had 18-week semesters.
Now...
You don't have over about 15 weeks of actual classwork, and not even that in the fall semester.
15 weeks of actual classwork.
The time applied has decreased.
The number of student credit hours that a student takes has decreased.
And the number of weeks it takes has decreased, and at the same time, the amount of information that he needs to gather has exploded.
Consequently, I'd say that when a fella gets his degree, nowadays, he's in a position to learn something about whatever work he goes into.
So he won't know what you're buying.
Looking back on your long teaching career, Professor Cassidy, have you ever regretted coming to A&M back in 1932?
No, never.
28, rather?
No, never.
Never regretted it?
You must not have got to go back to Mississippi too much back in the 30s.
No, I didn't.
My freshman year, I went back at the end of the whole year.
Then on I went home on Christmas, but that's all.
Hitchhiking back home?
Yeah.
Back then it was easy to hitchhike, compared to now.
Yeah, it was.
When did it become so difficult to hitchhike?
Thugs.
When?
About what time?
The 60s or 50s?
I guess some of that coincides with all of the Berkeley activities.
where they no longer, a student was no longer recognized as a person following an honorable, with honorable intentions.
But back in my day, people picked you up, glad to pick you up if you have company on a long trip.
No problem.
Well, it may be about time for me to get back to my retirement.
I didn't think of anything in particular.
What were you doing in retirement, by the way?
Were you doing anything in particular?
Well, for about the first four years of that period, I did considerable consulting.
I did some consulting long before I retired.
I went to consulting about more so than the research route.
I was working on real problems for real people,
and not on something hypothetical.

I could get all of the research work I could handle and would either go into it as a full business or when I found out that I would have to keep the same set of books as though I were General Motors or something,
on withholding tax, the workman's compensation, social security deductions.
He had to keep all of those books and all.
If a fella doesn't have a pretty sizable staff the way he has a secretary who does the bulk of all of that filing work for him,
You have to have a pretty big operation or else confine yourself to a strictly one-man operation.
And I throttled back after that.
And then, after so long a time, I had a heart attack and that throttled it back.
I still do a little research.
I mean, still a little consulting.
When did you have your appointment?
In September of 79.
Looking back on it, not necessarily from an engineering standpoint.
There was July.
Looking back on your life, Professor Cassidy,
Could you say, has there been any particular decade in which you've been alive that you thought was better than the other decades, not necessarily related to engineering?
The 60s could have been.
I think maybe the 50s were.
You think the 50s were a better time to live in than the 80s?
Well, now, in the 80s, right now, it all depends.
The people that have jobs, that have a living, insurance somehow, they're doing fine.
But the people that are unemployed, they're not doing so well.
What do you think is the cause of the high rate of unemployment?
Do you think there's any one single cause?
We can't go along with an unbalanced budget year after year after year, getting worse and worse and more worse without the chips falling someplace.
Furthermore,
In our foreign trade, we have had a deficit.
Foreign trade now, year after year after year, and when you buy more than you sell, foreign countries.
I think that even includes the giveaways.
You can't do that without some time or another, otherwise the chips are going to fall.
and they're falling right now.
Do you think there's any solution to the economic problem today?
They've got to cut out all this throwing money.
They've got a problem, what do they do?
They throw money at it just like you're throwing baseball.
Some people claim that too much has already been cut out of things and delivered today.
I think some of those same people get out and go to work, why, that would help solve the problem too.
I would like to see a little Americanism preached.
I got a son, we got a son that has a Datsun pickup.
I call that a Pearl Harbor pickup.
Sometimes it's an illusion that the foreign product is better.
Just wait until that day comes around when you need to repair it.
sometimes that's a real illusion right i've heard some people say that i've heard others say that until we have a balance
and what we take in and what we spend.
The government's no different than what you are or what I am.
Well, you think that President Reagan probably is on the right track.
He's trying to be.
He's never going to pull any Congress to deal with.
Congress more nearly than the Senate.
I'm a recipient of Social Security.
But if they keep on increasing the Social Security with this so-called consumer price index route, it is going to exponentially
It will go beyond all imagination.
There's no way.
I think that probably more than anything else, maybe the cost of living increases coming on that.
Like you said, an exponential increase.
I think it's nearly double what it was 10 years ago.
The cost of living goes to all of the government employees.
It goes to all of the
It goes to all of us.
It goes to all retirees in the military.
It goes to all the active duty in the military.
It goes to all of the bureaucrats.
And one of the bureaucracies is the worst thing in the world that we've got.
You get a little pimp going here, and it wants to enlarge itself, king the belly.
Well, we've kind of gotten off the topic there quite a ways with engineering.
Is there anything else you want to say before we close?
No, but when you go to other institutions, you can come back and take pride in A&M is what it is.
Thank you very much for spending the afternoon with us, Professor Cass.
I enjoyed visiting with you.
Appreciate your time.
